\insrsid13787376  Standards Dialog Box}}}{\insrsid13787376  }{\cs15\fs18\cf1\up6\insrsid13787376 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\ql \li0\ri0\sl-240\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\cs15\fs18\up6\insrsid13787376 #}{\insrsid13787376  ID_STANDARDSDIALOG}}}{\insrsid13787376  }{\cs15\fs18\cf1\up6\insrsid13787376 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\ql \li0\ri0\sl-240\slmult1
\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\cs15\fs18\up6\insrsid13787376 K}{\insrsid13787376  Standard; Dialog Box}}}{\insrsid13787376  Standards Dialog Box
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid13787376    This dialog bo
x is used to display and set parameters of the standards to be used when calibrating the process, such as the component name, the response factor, and the concentration of the component in each standard (up to 4 standards can be used for calibration). The
 check mark shows the component to be used as a reference. To set parameters for the standards of any component, click on the corresponding line and then click the }{\b\insrsid13787376 Edit }{\insrsid13787376 button. An  }{\ul\insrsid13787376 
Edit Standard Dialog Box}{\v\dbch\af11\insrsid13787376 \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ID_EDITSTANDARDDIALOG}{\insrsid13787376  will pop up which allows to fi
ll in the concentration of the selected component in the standard (up to four standards can be used), and to check the particular component as a reference one. 
\par    The }{\b\insrsid13787376 Calibration}{\insrsid13787376  button opens the }{\uldb\insrsid13787376 Calibration Graph Window}{\v\dbch\af11\insrsid13787376 \hich\af0\dbch\af11\loch\f0 ID_CALIBRATIONDIALOG}{\insrsid13787376 
 that displays the graph of the selected component's concentration as a function of the component's peak height. In case of a multiple standard calibration, the graph is drawn as straight lines between the successive calibration points from the calibratio
n
 runs made with available standards (the origin is included as the case of zero concentration), and reflects the linear approximation approach between the nearest calibration points (the ones above and below the particular peak height) used in calculation
s of the concentrations of the components from the analysis data. In case the calibration was done with the only standard, the linear approximation is used (a straight line through the calibration point and the origin).   
\par }\pard\plain \s1\ql \li0\ri0\sb280\sa120\sl-320\slmult0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs24\cf2\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid13787376 \page }{
